Remove broken TAILQ_FIRST restore from pt_backend_enable.

The previous patch used TAILQ_FIRST(&ctx->threads) to restore
cpu->ctx on switch-in.  This always picked thread 0's pt_ctx,
even when a different thread was switching in.  For multi-threaded
programs this caused:

  1. Worker thread's PT data written to thread 0's ToPA buffer,
     contaminating thread 0's trace with the wrong thread's
     instructions.

  2. xrstors loading thread 0's save area on a CPU about to run
     a different thread — mismatched XSAVE state causes a GPF
     (general protection fault → kernel panic).

The fix is to simply remove the TAILQ_FIRST restore.  It was never
needed: hwt_switch_in() calls hwt_backend_configure() immediately
before hwt_backend_enable(), and pt_backend_configure() already
sets pt_pcpu[cpu_id].ctx to the correct thread's pt_ctx by looking
up the thread_id in the TAILQ:

    TAILQ_FOREACH(thr, &ctx->threads, next) {
        if (thr->thread_id != thread_id) continue;
        pt_ctx = (struct pt_ctx *)thr->private;
        break;
    }
    ...
    pt_pcpu[cpu_id].ctx = pt_ctx;

Apply from /usr/src (on top of existing hwt-race-fixes patches):
  patch -p1 < /path/to/pt-enable-fix.patch

---
--- a/sys/amd64/pt/pt.c
+++ b/sys/amd64/pt/pt.c
@@ -514,22 +514,10 @@
 static void
 pt_backend_enable(struct hwt_context *ctx, int cpu_id)
 {
-	struct hwt_thread *thr;
-
 	if (ctx->mode == HWT_MODE_CPU)
 		return;

 	KASSERT(curcpu == cpu_id,
 	    ("%s: attempting to start PT on another cpu", __func__));
-
-	/*
-	 * Restore the per-CPU context pointer.  pt_backend_disable clears
-	 * cpu->ctx on every switch-out; we must re-set it here so that
-	 * pt_cpu_start can find the tracing context on the new CPU.
-	 */
-	thr = TAILQ_FIRST(&ctx->threads);
-	if (thr != NULL && thr->private != NULL)
-		pt_pcpu[cpu_id].ctx = (struct pt_ctx *)thr->private;
-
 	pt_cpu_start(NULL);
 	CPU_SET(cpu_id, &ctx->cpu_map);
 }
